{"key":"processedPost-19432040","value":{"id":19432040,"first":19429909,"last":19432832,"when":1389966095,"utime":"01/17/14 03:41 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>fourleaf033 said:</b><br />Is a 45 liter per minute air pump running 24/7 too much for a 18 gallon tub? <br /></blockquote><br /><br />It depends on how many fish you have.<br /><br />Seriously, air pumps tend to dry out substrates.&nbsp; I'd just let the natural air currents in the room exchange air.&nbsp; It also makes little difference the size of the tub, but rather how many substrates you have in there, which you didn't address.<br /><br /><i>Air exchanges per hour</i> is not a valid measurement of fresh air requirements for mushrooms because it doesn't take into account the amount of CO2 producing substrate mass, but instead focuses on a non-important feature such as the size of the grow chamber or room.&nbsp; The bottom line is you want the CO2 less than 1000 ppm for best performance.<br />RR","title":"Re: air pump post"}}